The first group of teachers will this week be trained on the new curriculum that will replace the 32-year-old 8-4-4 curriculum.The Kenya Institute of Curriculum Development said 1,888 teachers from the 47 counties will today be taken through the syllabus that was endorsed by the institute&rsquo;s academic committee last Thursday. The training ends on Thursday.&ldquo;We have ensured no player in the education sector is left behind. For the first time, even those with special needs are working on the curriculum on their own to ensure it meets their needs,&rdquo; KICD director, Dr Julius Jwan, said.Teaching for the pilot phase will begin on May 29.